# PC Volume Controller — serial-port access without group juggling.
#
# The controller is an ESP32-S3 speaking native USB CDC, so it enumerates under
# Espressif's vendor ID (0x303a) as /dev/ttyACM*. Distros disagree on which group
# owns that node (uucp on Arch, dialout on Debian/Ubuntu/Fedora), and either way
# the user has to log out and back in for the membership to take effect.
#
# TAG+="uaccess" sidesteps all of it: systemd-logind grants an ACL on the device
# to whoever owns the active local session, applied the moment it's plugged in.
# Remote/SSH sessions deliberately don't get it.
#
# Two matches, because the board exists in both wirings. Native USB CDC boards
# come up under Espressif's VID; the v1.4 PCB routes serial through a WCH CH343
# bridge, which enumerates under QinHeng's VID with the ESP32 invisible behind it.
#
# The CH343 match is pinned to its product ID as well. VID 1a86 alone covers half
# the cheap USB-serial adapters in existence (CH340 especially), and handing an
# ACL to every one of them plugged into the machine is more than this needs.
#
# Still unmatched: boards behind a CP210x or FTDI bridge. Those need the group
# route (`uucp` on Arch, `dialout` elsewhere) — `lsusb` will tell you which you have.
SUBSYSTEM=="tty", ATTRS{idVendor}=="303a", TAG+="uaccess"
SUBSYSTEM=="tty", ATTRS{idVendor}=="1a86", ATTRS{idProduct}=="55d3", TAG+="uaccess"
